      {
        "id": "n14",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 687.5495909929434,
          "y": 2086.059389167513
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "# Range matched filter from the transmit reference chirp (already built in n2).\n# Normalisation: divide H_range by sqrt(chirp_energy). This is the standard SAR\n# matched-filter L2-norm normalisation that gives processing gain = sqrt(Tp*B)\n# voltage (≈ +28.7 dB for Tp*B=750), matching the textbook \"pulse compression\n# gain\" of sqrt(time-bandwidth product). Without this, unnormalised FFTs leave\n# a per-bin gain of L (≈ +57 dB) on top, exaggerating the focused peak.\nt_ref = (np.arange(Nr) - Nr // 2) * dt_r\n_ref = ((np.abs(t_ref) <= Tp/2).astype(np.float32) * np.exp(1j*np.pi*Kr*t_ref**2)).astype(np.complex64)\nchirp_energy_rg = float(np.sum(np.abs(_ref) ** 2))   # = Tp*Fs (samples), ~750 for our setup\nH_range = np.conj(np.fft.fft(np.fft.ifftshift(_ref))) / np.sqrt(chirp_energy_rg)\ns_rc = np.fft.ifft(np.fft.fft(s_raw, axis=1) * H_range[None, :], axis=1).astype(np.complex64)\nprint('range-compressed: shape=%s  norm /sqrt(Tp*Fs)=%.1f → gain=+%.1f dB  peak=%.3g'\n      % (s_rc.shape, np.sqrt(chirp_energy_rg), 10*np.log10(chirp_energy_rg), float(np.abs(s_rc).max())))\n",
            "label": "Range Compression",
            "spec": "PROCESSING (RDA step 1): compress each range line by matched filtering with the conjugate of the transmit chirp.\n\nPhysics:\n  H_range = conj( FFT( ifftshift(ref_chirp) ) )\n  s_rc = IFFT( FFT(s_raw, axis=range) * H_range )\nConcentrates each target's chirp smear into a sharp range peak."
          },
          "codeCollapsed": true,
          "executionOrder": 27
        },
        "width": 400,
        "style": {}
      },
      {
        "id": "n15",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 1149.8813333536234,
          "y": 2090.346417141425
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "S_rd  = np.fft.fftshift(np.fft.fft(s_rc, axis=0), axes=0).astype(np.complex64)\nf_eta = np.fft.fftshift(np.fft.fftfreq(Na, 1/PRF))\nprint('range-Doppler: shape=%s  f_eta=[%.1f, %.1f] Hz' % (S_rd.shape, f_eta.min(), f_eta.max()))",
            "label": "Azimuth FFT (Range-Doppler)",
            "spec": "PROCESSING (RDA step 2): FFT along azimuth (slow-time) to enter the Range-Doppler domain. Range axis is never shifted; azimuth is fftshift-ed so the Doppler axis is centered.\n\n  S_rd  = fftshift( FFT(s_rc, axis=azimuth) )\n  f_eta = fftshift( fftfreq(Na, 1/PRF) )   # Doppler axis"
          },
          "codeCollapsed": true,
          "executionOrder": 28
        },
        "width": 400,
        "style": {}
      },
      {
        "id": "n16",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 1639.1422549275474,
          "y": 2074.7905512635116
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "delta_R = (lam**2 * R0 * f_eta**2) / (8 * V**2)      # (Na,) m\ndelta_t = 2 * delta_R / c\nf_r = np.fft.fftfreq(Nr, dt_r)                        # range freq (not shifted)\nS_rd_rf = np.fft.fft(S_rd, axis=1)\nshift = np.exp(1j * 2 * np.pi * f_r[None, :] * delta_t[:, None])\nS_rd_rcmc = np.fft.ifft(S_rd_rf * shift, axis=1).astype(np.complex64)\nrange_cell_m = c * dt_r / 2\nprint('RCMC: max RCM = %.3f m = %.1f range cells' % (delta_R.max(), delta_R.max()/range_cell_m))",
            "label": "RCMC",
            "spec": "PROCESSING (RDA step 3): Range Cell Migration Correction. In the Range-Doppler domain a target's energy lies on a parabola across range cells; RCMC straightens it via a range-frequency phase shift.\n\n  delta_R = lam^2 * R0 * f_eta^2 / (8 V^2)   (narrow-beam)\n  shift   = exp(j 2pi f_r * 2 delta_R / c)\n  S_rd_rcmc = IFFT( FFT(S_rd, axis=range) * shift )"
          },
          "codeCollapsed": true,
          "executionOrder": 29
        },
        "width": 400,
        "style": {}
      },
      {
        "id": "n17",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 2119.76374767998,
          "y": 2072.6625246679473
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "# Method C: range-DEPENDENT azimuth compression. Each range column gets its own\n# azimuth FM rate Ka(r) from its own slant range, instead of one Ka fixed at R0.\n# Needed once the swath is wide (verified: from ~+-1 km the range-independent\n# filter mis-places far targets by 1-2 azimuth cells; Ka(r) corrects it). At\n# narrow swath it is identical to the old single-Ka filter, so this is a safe\n# always-on upgrade. RCMC (n16) stays parabolic: verified that the exact\n# hyperbolic dR makes NO difference even at B=600 MHz / +-2 km, so azimuth Ka(r)\n# is the only fix that matters for wide-swath focusing.\n#\n# Normalisation note: empirically the azimuth FFT+H_az+IFFT chain already\n# produces gain ≈ sqrt(Na) (= textbook SAR azimuth coherent-integration gain),\n# because NumPy's FFT (no norm) + IFFT (1/N norm) combined with the LFM chirp's\n# energy spread naturally gives this. No extra normalisation needed here.\nR_col  = R0 + (t_r - t_r_center) * c / 2              # slant range per range column [m]\nKa_col = 2 * V**2 / (lam * R_col)                     # azimuth FM rate per column (Nr,)\nH_az   = np.exp(-1j * np.pi * (f_eta[:, None]**2) / Ka_col[None, :])   # (Na, Nr)\nimg    = np.fft.ifft(np.fft.ifftshift(S_rd_rcmc * H_az, axes=0), axis=0).astype(np.complex64)\nprint('focused image: shape=%s  Ka(R0)=%.1f Hz/s  Ka range=[%.1f, %.1f]  peak=%.1f  (azimuth gain ≈ +%.1f dB)'\n      % (img.shape, 2*V**2/(lam*R0), Ka_col.min(), Ka_col.max(), np.abs(img).max(),\n         10*np.log10(Na)))\n",
            "label": "Azimuth Compression",
            "spec": "PROCESSING (RDA step 4): focus in azimuth with the conjugate azimuth matched filter, then inverse azimuth FFT -> focused complex image.\n\nMETHOD C (range-dependent azimuth FM rate). Each range column uses its own slant range R_col = R0 + range_offset, so its own Ka(r):\n  Ka(r) = 2 V^2 / (lam * R_col)            # per range column (Nr,)\n  H_az  = exp(-j pi f_eta^2 / Ka(r))       # 2-D (Na, Nr), conjugate, focuses at az=0\n  img   = IFFT( ifftshift( S_rd_rcmc * H_az ) )\n\nWhy: a single Ka fixed at R0 mis-focuses far-range targets once the swath is wide. Verified (verify_rcmc_swath_sweep.py): the range-independent filter mis-places corner targets by 1-2 azimuth cells from ~+-1 km swath; Ka(r) brings them back to 0. At narrow swath Ka(r) == single-Ka, so this is a safe always-on upgrade.\n\nNote on RCMC (n16): kept parabolic on purpose. The exact-hyperbolic dR was verified to make NO measurable difference even at B=600 MHz / +-2 km (R0 ~ 567 km geometry), so azimuth Ka(r) is the ONLY focusing fix that matters for wide swath; do not 'fix' the RCMC unless geometry changes drastically.\n\nResult: each point target collapses to its impulse response (IRF), correctly placed across the full swath."
          },
          "codeCollapsed": true,
          "executionOrder": 30
        },
        "width": 400,
        "style": {}
      },
